04454nam a22006735i 9780292795549DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927955497 a10.7560/7147862doi  a(DE-B1597)587299  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF394.E86bW35 2007eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a976.4/4922221 aWalter, Tamra Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEspíritu Santo de Zúñiga :bA Frontier Mission in South Texas /cTamra Lynn Walter. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tOne INTRODUCTION -- tTwo THE HISTORICAL RECORD -- tThree THE ARCHAEOLOGICAL RECORD -- tFour MISSION ARCHITECTURE -- tFive INVESTIGATIONS AT RELATED SITES -- tSix MISSION MATERIAL CULTURE -- tSeven MISSION FOODWAYS The Faunal Collection -- tEight CONCLUSIONS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early part of the eighteenth century, the Spanish colonial mission Espíritu Santo de Zúñiga was relocated from far south Texas to a site along the Guadalupe River in Mission Valley, Victoria County. This mission, along with a handful of others in south Texas, was established by the Spaniards in an effort to Christianize and civilize the local Native American tribes in the hopes that they would become loyal Spanish citizens who would protect this new frontier from foreign incursions. With written historical records scarce for Espíritu Santo, Tamra Walter relies heavily on material culture recovered at this site through a series of recent archaeological investigations to present a compelling portrait of the Franciscan mission system. By examining findings from the entire mission site, including the compound, irrigation system, quarry, and kiln, she focuses on questions that are rarely, if ever, answered through historical records alone: What was daily life at the mission like? What effect did the mission routine have on the traditional lifeways of the mission Indians? How were both the Indians and the colonizers changed by their frontier experiences, and what does this say about the missionization process? Walter goes beyond simple descriptions of artifacts and mission architecture to address the role these elements played in the lives of the mission residents, demonstrating how archaeology is able to address issues that are not typically addressed by historians. In doing so, she presents an accurate portrait of life in South Texas at this time. This study of Mission Espíritu Santo will serve as a model for research at similar early colonial sites in Texas and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFood habitszTexaszMission ValleyxHistory. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezTexaszMission Valley. 0aIndians of North AmericazTexaszMission ValleyxAntiquities. 0aMaterial culturezTexaszMission ValleyxHistory. 0aSpaniardszTexaszMission ValleyxAntiquities. 0aSpanish mission buildingszTexaszMission Valley. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71478640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795549/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK